	abstract = {The basic concepts of frequentist and Bayesian techniques for the identiﬁcation of model parameters and the estimation of model prediction uncertainty are brieﬂy reviewed. A simple example with synthetically generated data sets of a model for microbial substrate conversion is used as a didactical tool for analyzing strengths and weaknesses of both techniques in the context of environmental system identiﬁcation. The comparison results in the practical superiority of the frequentist technique in the case of identiﬁable model parameters (computational efﬁciency). However, in the case of poor parameter identiﬁablility, the conceptual advantage of the estimation of parameter distributions and the use of prior knowledge make the Bayesian approach more recommendable. Because in environmental system identiﬁcation prior knowledge often makes the use of overparametrized models necessary, Bayesian techniques are very important in this ﬁeld and should more often be used. © 1999 Elsevier Science B.V. All rights reserved.},
